</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Notable Features: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Flipper">Flippers</a> (2), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Pop_Bumper">Pop&nbsp;bumpers</a> (3), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Rollunder_Spinner">Rollunder&nbsp;spinner</a> (1), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Captive_Ball">Captive&nbsp;ball</a> (1), <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Kick-out_Hole">Kick-out&nbsp;holes</a> (2), Left <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Kickback">kickback</a> lane. <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">Playfield</a> is manually rotated under a stationary glass top.<br><br>The only other Solid State game to have a rotating <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">playfield</a> is <span title="Click here to open a new window and display Midway's 1978 'Rotation VIII'"><a target="game2019" href="machine.cgi?id=2019">Midway's 1978 'Rotation VIII'</a></span>. Rotor Table Games Company made several electromechanical games in the 1930's that had rotating <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">playfields</a>. One example is <span title="Click here to open a new window and display Rotor Table Games Co, Incorporated's 'Confucius Say'"><a target="game4695" href="machine.cgi?id=4695">Rotor Table Games Co, Incorporated's 'Confucius Say'</a></span>.<P></td></tr>
